The missing (`__ne__`) method produces unexpected results. The code below shows it:


```
class T(object):

	def __init__(self, value):
		self.v = value

	def __eq__(self, other):
		return self.v == other


class T2(T):

	def __ne__(self, other):
		return not self == other



assert T(5) == 5
assert T(5) != 5

assert T2(5) == 5
assert (T2(5) != 5) == False

```

